y, remained a rival world view that was perceived by many Christian thinkers as a serious threat to their own intellectual identity. This problematic relationship was to become even more complex during the following centuries. Byzantine authors made numerous attempts to harmonize Neoplatonic doctrines with Christianity as well as to criticize, refute and even condemn them. The papers assembled in this volume discuss a number of specific questions and concerns that drew the interest of Byzantine scholars in different periods towards Neoplatonic sources in an attempt to identify and explore the central issues in the reception of Neoplatonic texts during the Byzantine era. This is the first volume of the sub-series "Byzantinisches Archiv - Series Philosophica", which will be dedicated to the rapidly growing field of research in Byzantine philosophical texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aNeoplatonism. 0aPhilosophyxByzantine EmpirexByzantine Empire. 0aPhilosophyzByzantine Empire. 4aByzanz. 4aNeuplatonismus. 4aPhilosophie. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aByzantium.  aNeoplatonism.  aPhilosophy.1 aAlexidze, Lela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuzzetta, Flavia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaray, Jesús de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeck, Udo Reinhold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarchetto, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMariev, Sergei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMariev, Sergei, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiles, Graeme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMtchedlidze, Magda, econtributor.4ctb4